[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Suggested action:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 1. Call Dr. Patel's office to confirm the dose change
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 2. If confirmed, update the discharge medication list
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m    in the patient's chart and emit a patient-facing
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m    confirmation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 3. If unconfirmed, instruct the patient on the correct
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m    dose
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Provenance chain attached:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Discharge medication list (hospital EHR, message ID
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   ABC-123, ingested 2 days ago)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - Patient and caregiver report (conversation ID
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   XYZ-789, captured today)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Care-team owner: assigned to primary care nurse C.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Lopez (queue: PCMH-coordination-medium)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m SLA: 4 business hours
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Performance benchmarks (illustrative, your mileage varies):**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Pre-bot baseline (existing care alone) | Post-bot (engaged members) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|---------------------------------------|----------------------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Referral closure rate (within protocol window) | 30-55% (varies by specialty and program) | 60-85% (after multi-quarter ramp) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Transition-of-care completion rate (per institutional protocol) | 40-65% | 70-90% |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Medication-reconciliation discrepancy detection rate | Variable, often low | Substantially higher (the assistant's distinctive value) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | 30-day readmission rate for engaged transitions | Baseline | 5-25% relative reduction (where outcomes mature) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Avoidable ED utilization rate | Baseline | 5-20% relative reduction (where outcomes mature) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Duplicate-service rate | Variable | Modest reduction in detected duplicates |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Caregiver-burden trajectory (Zarit Burden Interview or similar) | Variable | Modest improvement in engaged caregivers |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Patient-and-caregiver-reported coordination experience | Variable | Generally positive, varies by program design |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Engagement attrition by 6 months | N/A | 25-50% (operational risk, similar to other longitudinal bots) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Citation-coverage rate | N/A | 95%+ as launch-gate target |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Seam-detection precision (sampled review) | N/A | 80-95% target across rules |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Seam-detection recall (sampled review) | N/A | 70-90% target across rules |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Per-active-member infrastructure cost | N/A | $4-12 per member per month |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Per-active-member total cost (including care-management workforce) | N/A | $30-100 per member per month |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Per-cohort outcome disparity | Often invisible | Monitored explicitly |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO: replace illustrative figures with measured results from the deployment. The ranges above are typical for hybrid AI-plus-human coordination programs but vary substantially with program design, target population, integration coverage, and engagement intensity. Published evidence for hybrid coordination programs includes peer-reviewed studies of programs from major payers, integrated delivery networks, post-discharge transition programs, and care-coordination platforms, with effect sizes varying. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Where it struggles:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Integration coverage gaps.** The assistant operates only as well as its ingestion. Patients whose primary care, hospital, pharmacy, and home-health are all integrated have a different experience than patients with partial coverage. Mitigation: explicit per-source coverage tracking, per-patient confidence calibration, transparent disclosure to the patient and caregiver about what the assistant does and does not know.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Provenance gaps.** When the assistant cannot trace an assertion back to a specific source, the assertion is suspect. Mitigation: provenance-as-architectural-primitive; faithfulness verification; safe-fallback templates when provenance is missing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Seam-detection-rule-engine maturity.** The first rules deployed catch the most common, well-understood seams (medication discrepancies, referral non-scheduling, transition-of-care incompleteness). The harder cases (subtle conflicting orders, complex cross-organizational coordination patterns) require multi-quarter rule-development with clinical-leadership ownership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Care-team adoption and trust.** A coordination assistant the care team does not trust or use is a coordination assistant whose value is invisible. Mitigation: clinical-leadership co-design, care-team-workflow integration, sampled-review with care-team feedback, structured failure-mode labeling.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Engagement attrition over months.** Patients and caregivers who initially engage may attrit over time as the immediate post-discharge or post-procedure pressure recedes. Mitigation: relationship-quality engineering, low-pressure check-in cadence, caregiver-burden-aware engagement timing, gentle re-engagement after silence, per-cohort attrition monitoring.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Cross-organizational consent friction.** Patients enrolling in coordination across organizations encounter consent friction that is genuinely confusing. Mitigation: plain-language consent UX, multilingual consent forms, cohort-specific guidance, opt-in granularity for sensitive categories.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Equity gaps in integration coverage.** Patients in well-resourced practices and well-resourced markets are better instrumented than patients in under-resourced practices and markets, who often have greater coordination needs. Mitigation: per-cohort monitoring as launch-gate; targeted integration investment for under-resourced sites; alternative integration paths (patient-mediated SMART on FHIR; HIE participation; payer-provided claims feeds).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Outcome attribution.** Engaged patients are not a random sample, and coordination outcomes have many confounders. Mitigation: matched-cohort or quasi-experimental analysis; recognition that observational correlation is suggestive, not causal; long-time-horizon commitment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Caregiver-burden interventions remain limited.** The assistant can take routine work off the caregiver's plate but cannot address the underlying caregiver-burden drivers (financial constraints, social isolation, the caregiver's own health needs). Mitigation: respite-and-support resource surfacing; integration with care-management for high-burden cases; explicit caregiver-burden tracking with care-management routing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Cross-organizational data quality remains uneven.** Pharmacy data feeds carry inconsistent medication-naming and dose representation. FHIR APIs from different EHRs return different shapes for the same clinical concept. Claims feeds lag clinical events by weeks to months. Mitigation: institutional-pharmacy-informatics partnership; FHIR normalization layer; per-source data-quality tracking; transparent disclosure of data-quality limitations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Sensitive-record handling complexity.** 42 CFR Part 2, state-specific mental-health record protections, state-specific HIV-record protections, genetic-test-result protections, and adolescent confidentiality each have category-specific rules. Mitigation: sensitive-record-classification at ingestion; per-category consent enforcement; legal-counsel review of state-specific rules; institutional policy with named ownership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Information Blocking rule navigation.** The Information Blocking rule requires certain data sharing; state-specific privacy regulations may limit it. Mitigation: legal-counsel-reviewed institutional posture; operational enforcement through the consent layer; documented decision rationale for any apparent tension.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Adversarial inputs.** Patients (or bad actors) attempting to extract information about other patients, manipulate seam-flag routing, bypass scope discipline, or test the system. Mitigation: input-safety pipeline with prompt-injection detection; output-safety pipeline; tool-Lambda patient_id-cross-check; per-language adversarial test corpus including coordination-specific injection cases.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Liability exposure for missed seams or mishandled escalations.** A coordination assistant that fails to detect a seam (e.g., a critical medication conflict; an overlooked discharge follow-up; a miscommunicated dose change) and a patient is subsequently harmed is a foreseeable liability exposure. Mitigation: rigorous seam-detection-rule sign-off; sampled review by clinical leadership; named clinical-leadership ownership per rule; FDA-strategy artifact maintained where applicable; institutional malpractice carrier involvement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Build-vs-buy positioning.** Several mature commercial coordination platforms offer adjacent capabilities. Mitigation: evaluate build-vs-buy explicitly; most major institutions run a hybrid that combines a thin orchestration layer in-house with vendor-supplied integration substrate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Long-term protocol drift.** Over years, coordination protocols evolve as clinical evidence accumulates and institutional practice changes. Mitigation: protocol-as-code with version control; annual review cycles; clinical-leadership signoff; deprecation policy.
